<DOC><DOCNO> AP881218-0047 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-18-88 1542EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-DEACorruption     12-18 0259</FIRST><SECOND>AM-DEA Corruption,0265</SECOND><HEAD>Three Former DEA Agents Investigated In Heroin Theft</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Asian heroin valued at $7.5 million apparentlydisappeared from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration regionaloffice, a newspaper reported Sunday.   More than five pounds of heroin vanished in separate incidents in1984 and 1985 after DEA agents seized the drugs as evidence, the LosAngeles Times reported, citing unnamed sources close to a corruptioninvestigation.   The probe has focused on the alleged corruption of former DEAagents John Anthony Jackson, Darnell Garcia and Wayne Countryman,who were indicted Dec. 7 on conspiracy and tax charges.   Federal investigators, according to the newspaper, have linkedJackson to the suspected theft of 2{ pounds of heroin from a DEAvault in 1984.   Jackson also participated in a 1985 heroin investigation in whichDEA undercover agents bought 15 pounds of heroin, but booked only 12pounds as evidence, according to the same unnamed sources.   Jackson, 39, who is being held without bail, declined a Timesrequest for an interview, the newspaper said. Attorneys representingthe three agents also declined to comment.   Prosecutors have said the three DEA agents were tied to cocainetrafficking and may have alerted Los Angeles drug kingpins tofederal investigations.   However, the only charges filed so far against the former agentsinvolve an alleged plot to defraud the Internal Revenue Service andmaking false statements on currency reports. The former agentsallegedly laundered more than $608,000 through Swiss bank accounts.   Countryman, 45, was released after posting $120,000 bail; Garcia,42, is a fugitive.</TEXT></DOC>